defaultGeneral rdefaultemarksdefault4
default. The NFRN 
defaultrecognise
defaults that there have been a number of high profile and high value raids and seizures of illicit cigarettes in recent months. Notably in July 2013, officers from HMRC arrested five people during raids across the Peterborough and Spalding areas as part of an investigation into a suspected case of £6 million worth of cigarette smuggling fraud
default. 
default5
default. 
defaultT
defaulthe NFRN 
defaultalso 
defaultacknowledges
default the recent publication of 
defaultthe National Audit Office’s report into the progress of HMRC’s implementation of its tobacco smuggling strategy
default. However
default it was evident from the report
default that given HMRC’s estimate that tobacco smuggling cost the Exchequer £1.9bn in lost revenue over the 2010-11 period, and that it did not meet any of its “more stretching” targets in 2012-13, further action is required
default to tackle the problem accordingly
default.
default 
default6
default. 
defaultThe consequences of t
defaultobacco smuggling 
defaulthave
default a
default direct and far-reaching
default 
defaultimpact
default on the businesses of our members. The availability of cheaper, but illicit 
defaulttobacco
default 
defaultcan 
defaultresult
default in cash-strapped consumers purchasing tobacco from alternative sources
default, at the expense of responsible and legitimate retailers
default.  Such behaviour not only impacts on the finances of businesses and the Treasury, but most importantly, on the health of consumers
default who consume 
defaultthe 
defaultillicit 
defaultproducts
default.
default7. It is also worth 
defaultnoting that smuggling also impacts on the under-age consumption of tobacco products. 
defaultUnlike responsible retailers, 
defaultsellers of illicit tobacco will not ask for I.D from custome
defaultrs who appear under-age. Therefore 
defaulttobacco smuggling provides an
default accessible
default avenue for those who wish to obtain tobacco 
defaultproducts 
defaultwhilst under-age. 
default8
default.
default Counterfeit cigarettes often pose additional health risks to those traditionally associated with smoking, due to the variety of ingredients used. A BBC investigation
default in 2012
default discovered that illicit cigarettes sold for purchase in Sussex, contained levels of cancer-causing chemicals that were far higher than those 
defaultfound 
defaultin the legal, regulated products
default.
default The NFRN would recommend that 
defaultgreater
default promotion 
defaultof
default the
default dangers of
default dubious ingredients and potential health impacts of counterfeit cigarettes should be undertaken
default, in order
default to educate 
defaultand
default discourage people from purchasing such products. 
default9
default. Whilst the NFRN supports the government in its aim to reduce the number of people who smoke and
default to 
defaultprevent young people from starting
default the habit
default, it must be acknowledged that recent legislation such as the tobacco display 
defaultban
default c
defaultould potentially result in unintended 
defaultand undesirable 
defaultconsequences.
default 
defaultWhen the ban comes in to force in small stores in 2015, 
defaultit raises the possibility that 
defaultconsumers
default may 
defaultturn away from legitimate retailers to illicit sources
default, 
defaultas a consequence of l
defaultegal transactions being made more difficult
default.
default 
defaultAlternatively,
default for those customers unaware of the tobacco display ban, a belief that their local store no longer stocks tobacco
default may encourage them to seek out more convenient but illegal sources
default.
default10
default. 
defaultThe NFRN
default also
default 
defaultconsiders the link between tobacco smuggling and organised crime 
defaultto be
default a major concern. An attempt to s
defaultmuggle 30 million cigarettes in
defaultto the UK through the Port
default of Southampton
default in March 2013, highlights both the scale and professionalism
default of
default some smuggling operations
default that take place
default.
default As a consequence of the findings of the NAO report, it would desirable for HMRC to be equipped with all of the necessary resources in order to tackle this problem efficiently.
default11
default. 
defaultThe NFRN are campaigning actively on a number of issues relating to smuggling, including the Tobacco Products Directive (TPD). 
defaultThe upcoming vote on the 
defaultTPD
default is a potential further complication in the fight against tobacco smuggling
default as t
defaulthe NFRN fears that if the directive is agreed, the 
defaultprohibition
default of ten packs,
default menthol cigarettes,
default slims, and the introduction of combined warnings (picture plus text) of 75% on both sides of the tobacco packet
default will 
defaultonly serve to 
defaultencourage
default smuggling
default and counterfeiting
default, as packets may be easier to copy and some products such as menthols will only be available via illicit sources
default. 
defaultAs the directive will leave the door open for the government to
default bring in plain packaging for tobacco products in 
defaultthe UK, the NFRN 
defaultis 
defaultconcern
defaulted
default that the packaging will be simpler and easier
default to counterfeit, resulting in a
default further 
defaultinflux of illicit tobacco. Similarly, 
defaultthose who wish to purchase 
defaultthe outlawed 
defaultitems
default may feel tempted to buy them illicitly. 
