defaultDeclaration of interestsdefault13
default.
default In 2012 the NFRN reorganised with the separation of the not-for-profit trade association from its commercial operations, NFRN Commercial Ltd.
defaultThe NFRNdefault14
default. The NFRN, while working with tobacco manufactures on issues of mutual concern, has no financial links or arrangements with any tobacco manufacturer.
default15
default. The NFRN does work with the Tobacco Retailer Association, Tobacco Manufacturers Association and campaign groups such as “Hands Off Our Packs” and “No Thank EU” on matters of common interest.  In August 2013 the NFRN assisted in arranging the distribution of campaign and information packs from the “No Thank EU” campaign to NFRN members across the country.
default16
default. The NFRN does not receive any funding from, nor does it fund, any of these groups.
default17
default.  NFRN policy is set by members at its Annual Conference.   Members of staff, including those who deal with tobacco manufacturers and campaign groups, are not permitted to take part in the policy debates at the Annual Conference.
default18
default. In the Republic of Ireland, Transatlantic Public Affairs, who also work for Philip Morris, have provided no cost public affairs advice to the local NFRN district.  Such advice is monitored by the Head Office Public Affairs team to ensure compliance with the aims and objectives of the NFRN.
default19
default. The Public Affairs team works for the NFRN and does not  have sight of commercial agreements between the NFRN, NFRN Commercial Ltd and third parties, whether they be tobacco manufacturers or not.
defaultNFRN Commercialdefault 
defaultLtddefault20
default. NFRN Commercial Ltd, a wholly owned subsidiary
default operated at arm’s length from 
defaultthe NFRN, maintains commercial relationships with most tobacco manufacturers.   As a result of these relationships an amount of £
default28,000
default pa is spent by tobacco manufacturers on advertising and sponsorship.   
default21
default. As these relationships are with NFRN Commercial Ltd, the companies have no influence over NFRN policy.
default22
default. Senior management ha
defaultve received a modest amount of 
defaulthospitality from tobacco manufacturers.
default All such hospitality is recorded and is available for inspection.
default As members of staff, they do not have any say in the adoption or revision of NFRN policy.
defaultNewtrade Publishing Ltddefault23
default. The NFRN also owns Newtrade Publishing Ltd, publishers inter alia of Retail Newsagent and Retail Express.   Newtrade Publishing Ltd is operated as an arm’s length organisation, with contact limited to senior NFRN management and the Communications and Public Affairs teams who deal with Newtrade Publishing Ltd staff as normal press contacts.   Newtrade Publishing Ltd publications have carried advertising from tobacco manufacturers but this is unrelated to the work of the NFRN.
defaultGeneral Principledefaultsdefault24
default. While the NFRN
default,
default NFRN Commercial
default Ltd and Newtrade Publishing Ltd
default believe that it is perfectly legitimate to have business relationships with the manufacturers of legal tobacco products, they are aware of the sensitivity of the sector and the potential for reputational risk.   The NFRN and NFRN Commercial Ltd therefore take a conservative approach to these relationships, ensuring that relationships are 
defaultfocused
default towards achieving the aims and objectives of the NFRN and that all commercial arrangements are proportionate to the service being provided
default. 
defaultWhether the current sanctions and penalties for tobacco smuggling are appropriatedefault25
default. 
defaultCurrently, 
defaultt
defaulthe NFRN considers that the sanctions and penalties for tobacco smuggling are not 
defaulta sufficient
default deterrent. 
defaultG
defaultiven that 1.7 billion cigarettes were reportedly seized in the period 2010-11
default, it would appear that the financial incentives of cigarette smuggling are continuing to outweigh the risks of r
defaulteceiving a sanction and/or 
defaultpenalty
default. 
default2
default6
default.
default This view i
defaults 
defaultendorsed
default by 
defaultAndrew Leggett
default, Deputy Director for Indirect Tax at HMRC
default, who gave evidence on the EU cigarette strategy
default to the House of Lords 
defaultSelect Committee on the European Union
default - Home Affairs, Health and Education (Sub-Committee F), which was held on Wednesday 24
defaultth
default July 2013. 
default2
default7
default. Leggett admitted that 
defaultlarge amounts of money could be made from illicit 
defaultcigarette sales, highlighting that a pack of “20 cigarettes is twice the price of an illicit pack of 20 cigarettes” 
defaultand considered that “at the moment the 
defaultbalance of risk and reward is a good one for tobacco default[smuggling] defaultgloballydefault”
default. 
default2
default8
default.
default It is important to note that w
defaulthils
defaultt the NFRN would 
defaultlike stronger deterrence’s
default for cigarette smugglers, 
defaultit would not 
defaultsupport
default measures which would place further burdens on those who are legitimate sellers
default of tobacco products
default.
default2
default9
default. The NFRN suggests that 
defaultattention
default also needs to be given to
default the different methods of
default deterring the consumer from purchasing illicit tobacco.
default For example, 
defaultin the Quebec region of Canada, 
defaultthey have opted to criminalise
default 
defaultconsumers of illicit tobacco
default through the 
defaultTobacco Tax Act
default, a policy the NFRN would encourage the committee to examine during its inquiry.
default30
default. Furthermore as mentioned previously in paragraph 6, the NFRN would encourage 
defaultraising
default 
defaultawareness of the ingredients and potential health implications that can 
defaultresult from
default the consumption of illicit tobacco products
