defaultThe possible impact of the introduction of standardized packaging in Ireland on the quantity and availability of illegal tobacco in the UKdefault3
default1
default. 
defaultThe NFRN disagrees with the introduction of standardised packaging for cigarettes in Ireland. Whilst the intention to make tobacco less attractive to consumers is a laudable aim, 
defaultwe consider that the policy 
defaultc
defaultould have unintended
default negative effects on consumers.
default 
defaultIt is worth noting that s
defaultince the introduction of the display ban in Ireland, 
defaultsmoking has not decreased but the proliferation of illicit tobacco has increased.
default3
default2
default. 
defaultOne
default unintended consequence of the policy if 
defaultintroduced
default could be that 
defaultthe number of counterfeit cigarettes could increase. As tobacco products would be subject to specific
default and generic
default packaging design requirements as set out by 
defaultstatute
default, there is a risk that essentially, a “how to” manual for counterfeiters is being produced
default. This combined with the fact that packs will be simpler in design, suggests that counterfeiting process will become easier, potentially leading to an increase in illicit tobacco.
default3
default3
default.
default HMRC have also conceded that “the simpler you make a package, the easier it is to counterfeit it”, however
default 
defaultthey 
defaultdid state
default the
defaultir belief that there
default was not the evidence available to 
default“to quantify the extent to which those risks would materialise
default”.
default3
default4
default. In addition, if the policy is implemented and it does lead to an increase in illicit tobacco as the NFRN 
defaultbelieves
default, this will have a knock on 
defaulteffect for legitimate retailers who provide a valuable service to communities,
default 
defaultpotentially putting some of our members out of business
default and 
defaultdetrimentally 
defaultimpacting upon the health of consumers
default.
default3
default5
default. 
defaultThe lack of evidence currently available is a further reason why the NFRN considers the decision on plain packaging in Ireland should be delayed. 
defaultI
defaultt would be sensible to wait until furth
defaulter data
default from Australia
default is published
default,
default so that there can be
default sufficient
default analysis and a fuller understanding of the potential 
defaultconsequences
default of the policy. 
defaultConclusiondefault3
default6
default.
default 
defaultWhilst the NFRN acknowledges the steps HMRC have taken to reduce tobacco smuggling, the volume of the illicit market is still far too
default high. This is
default to the detriment 
defaultof both 
defaultthe consumer’s health and the finances of hard-working, independent businesses in the retail and convenience sector. 
defaultWith the upcoming vote on the TPD rapidly approaching and the potential effects of the directive if passed on tobacco smuggling, the NFRN welcomes the committee’s decision to launch an inquiry into this issue. 
